Cline tells the gripping story of how the end was brought about by multiple interconnected failures, ranging from invasion and revolt to earthquakes, drought, famine, and the cutting of international trade routes. Bringing to life a vibrant multicultural world, he draws a sweeping panorama of the empires of the age and shows that it may have been their very interdependence that hastened their dramatic collapse. Now revised and updated, 1177 B.C. sheds light on the complex ties that gave rise to, and eventually destroyed, the flourishing civilizations of the Late Bronze Age—and set the stage for the emergence of classical Greece and, ultimately, our world today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2022) 0aBronze agezMediterranean Region. 0aSea Peoples. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aAdad-nirari I.  aAegean civilizations.  aAkhenaten.  aAlaksandu.  aAlalakh.  aAlashiya.  aAmarna.  aAmenhotep III.  aAmmurapi.  aAmun.  aAmurru (god).  aAncient Near East.  aAncient history.  aArchaeology.  aAshkelon.  aAssyria.  aBabylonia.  aBronze Age.  aCanaan.  aCarchemish.  aCarl Blegen.  aCity-state.  aCivilization.  aClay tablet.  aClimate change.  aDeir el-Bahari.  aDisaster.  aDrought.  aEastern Mediterranean.  aEgyptians.  aEgyptology.  aEighteenth Dynasty of Egypt.  aEpigraphy.  aFamine.  aGeography of Greece.  aGreat power.  aGreeks.  aHatshepsut.  aHattusa.  aHazor.  aHebrews.  aHeinrich Schliemann.  aHittites.  aHoard.  aHurrians.  aHyksos.  aIron Age.  aIsraelites.  aKamose.  aKassites.  aKing of Egypt.  aKnossos.  aKynos.  aLate Bronze Age collapse.  aMediterranean Sea.  aMegadrought.  aMerneptah.  aMinoan civilization.  aMinoan eruption.  aMinoan pottery.  aMitanni.  aMortuary temple.  aMycenae. 